# Step 3: Setup 2-way trust between AWS Managed AD &amp; on-premises AD

## Part 1: Allow communication between AWS Managed AD &amp; on-prem AD

1. Log in to your AWS account and access the Security Group page under EC2. https://console.aws.amazon.com/vpc/home?region=us-east-1#securityGroups:
2. In the Filter/Search bar type Controller and hit enter. This will show you the AD/AWS Directory Service Security groups:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

Look at the descriptions, you will see two &quot;Domain Controller&quot; Security group. These correspond to the two on-prem domain controllers networks that was built as a part of AD quickstart. You will also see the Security group that was created for your AWS Directory Service &quot;AWS created security group for xxx directory controllers&quot;. Take note of these security group ID&#39;s.

3. Click on the Security Group named &quot;d-xxxxxxx\_controllers&quot;
4. Click the Outbound Rules tab and click Edit
5. You will need to create two Allow All Outbound rules, one for each Domain Controller Security group set as the destination as follows:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

6. Click Save
7. Now you will create rules to allow AWS Directory Service traffic to each of the on-prem Domain Controller Security Groups
8. Click on one of the &quot;Domain Controller&quot; Security Group
9. Click Inbound Rules and click Edit
10. Create an Allow All inbound rule and specify the AWS Directory Service Security Group as the source:

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

11. Click Save
12. Repeat these steps for the other On-Premise Domain Controller Security Group

## Part 2: Enable Kerberos pre-authentication on both user accounts

User accounts in both directories must have Kerberos preauthentication enabled. This is the default, but it is important to verify:

1. First, we'll update the security group for the Remote Desktop Gateway Security Group.
2. In the Filter/Search bar type RDGW and hit enter. This will show you the Remote Desktop Gateway Security group. Select Inbound Rules, Edit Rules, and change the "Source IP" to the correct IP, which can be found at http://myipaddress.com/ . Ensure the IP has the /32 at the end in CIDR notation.
3. Connect to your on-premise domain controller via the RDGW. You can find the public IP address or DNS name in the EC2 console. The name of the instance will be &quot;RDGW&quot;

Note: You can login to the RDGW using &quot;ONPREM\admin&quot; as username and password you set during the AD quickstart.

4. Once you login to RDGW, you can RDP again from here to one of the domain controllers (10.0.1.10 or 10.0.2.10).
5. Once you login to the domain controller, open Server Manager.
6. On the Tools menu, choose Active Directory Users and Computers.
7. Choose the Users folder and open the context (right-click) menu for the admin account listed in the right pane. Choose Properties.
8. Choose the Account tab. In the Account options list, scroll down and ensure that Do not require Kerberos preauthentication is not checked.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

## Part 3: Configure Conditional Forwarder on On-Prem Domain

You will need to configure conditional forwarders on both domain (on-prem &amp; Managed AD) so domain members in each domain can resolve name in the other domain. This is also a pre-requisite before you can setup trust between the domains.

1. Sign into the AWS Management Console and open the [AWS Directory Service console](https://console.aws.amazon.com/directoryservicev2/) at https://console.aws.amazon.com/directoryservicev2/.
2. In the navigation pane, select Directories.
3. Click on the directory ID of your AWS Managed Microsoft AD.
4. On the Details page, take note of the values in Directory name and the DNS address of your directory.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

5. Using Microsoft Remote Desktop, connect to the &quot;RDGW&quot; using your ONPREM\admin credentials.
6. Once connected to the RDGW, use Microsoft Remote Desktop to connect to DC1/DC2 using the ONPREM\admin credentials.
7. Open Server Manager.
8. On the Tools menu, choose DNS.
9. In the console tree, expand the DNS server of the domain for which you are setting up the trust. In our case it is DC1.onprem.local
10. In the console tree, choose Conditional Forwarders. Right-click and choose New conditional forwarder.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

11. In DNS domain, type the fully qualified domain name (FQDN) of your AWS Managed Microsoft AD (cloud.local).
12. Under IP addresses of the master servers, add the IP&#39;s of your AWS Managed Microsoft AD directory, which you noted earlier. 

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

13. Note: After entering the DNS addresses, you may get a &quot;timeout&quot; or &quot;unable to resolve&quot; error. You can ignore these errors.
14. Select Store this conditional forwarder in Active Directory, and replicate it as follows.
15. Select All DNS servers in this domain, and then choose OK.

## Part 3: Configure on-premises trust relationship

In this section, you configure a two-way trust. However, if you create a one-way trust, be aware that the trust directions on each of your domains must be complementary. For example, if you create a one-way, outgoing trust on your on-premises domain, you need to create a one-way, incoming trust on your AWS Managed Microsoft AD.

1. Log onto RDGW through Remote Desktop then login to DC1/DC2.
2. Open Server Manager and on the Tools menu, click on  **Active Directory Domains and Trusts****.**
3. Open the context (right-click) menu of your domain and choose Properties.
4. Choose the Trusts tab and choose New trust. Type the name of your AWS Managed AD **cloud.local** and click Next.
5. Choose  **Forest trust**. Click Next.
6. Choose  **Two-way**. Click Next.
7. Choose  **This domain only**. Click  **Next**.
8. Choose  **Forest-wide authentication**. Click  **Next**.
9. Type a Trust password. Make sure to remember this password as you will need it when setting up the trust for your AWS Managed Microsoft AD.
10. In the next dialog box, confirm your settings and choose Next. Confirm that the trust was created successfully and again choose Next.
11. Choose No, do not confirm the outgoing trust. Click Next.
12. Choose No, do not confirm the incoming trust. Click Next.
13. To close this wizard, select "Finish". 

## Part 5: Configure AWS Managed AD trust relationship

As a last step, you will need to configure the trust relationship for your AWS Managed Microsoft AD. Because you created a two-way trust on the on-premises domain, you will also create a two-way trust on your AWS Managed Microsoft AD.

1. Sign into the AWS Management Console and open the AWS Directory Service console at https://console.aws.amazon.com/directoryservicev2/.
2. On the Directories page, click on your AWS Managed Microsoft AD.
3. On the Directory details page, select the Networking &amp; security tab.
4. In the Trust relationships section, choose Actions, and then select Add trust relationship.
5. On the Add a trust relationship page, select Forest Trust, and type the FQDN of your on-premises domain, onprem.local. (Type the same trust password that you used when creating the trust on your on-premises domain. Specify the direction, in this case we choose Two-way.
6. In the Conditional forwarder field, enter the IP address of your on-premises DNS server. In this case, enter 10.0.1.10.
7. (Optional) Choose Add another IP address and enter a second IP address for your on-premises DNS server. In this example it will be 10.0.2.10.
8. Click Add to continue.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

9. You will find the status of the trust changes to Creating. After a few minutes, this should change to Verified.

 ![](data:image/*;base64,)

10. You now have a trust relationship between your on-premises domain (onprem.local) and your AWS Managed Microsoft AD (cloud.local).
